UNIX BASIC COMMANDS

1.pwd (Print Working Directory)
This command shows the current directory you are working in.
Example:
pwd

2.ls (List)
This command lists files and folders in the current directory.
ls → shows files
ls -l → shows details like permissions, size, date
ls -a → shows hidden files
Example:
ls -la

3.cd (Change Directory)
This command is used to move from one directory to another.
cd foldername → move into folder
cd .. → move one level back
cd ~ → go to home directory

4.mkdir (Make Directory)
This command creates a new folder.
Example:
mkdir notes

## 5.rmdir (Remove Directory)
This command deletes an empty directory.
Example:
rmdir notes

6.touch
This command creates an empty file.
Example:
touch file1.txt

7.cat (Concatenate)
This command displays the content of a file.
Example:
cat file1.txt

8.echo
This command prints text or writes text into a file.

overwrites the file

9.appends content to the file

Example:
echo Hello World > file1.txt
echo New Line >> file1.txt

10.cp (Copy)
This command copies files or folders.
Example:
cp file1.txt file2.txt
cp -r folder1 folder2

11.mv (Move / Rename)
This command moves or renames files.
Example:
mv file1.txt newfile.txt
mv file.txt foldername/

12.rm (Remove)
This command deletes files or folders.
Example:
rm file1.txt
rm -r foldername

13.clear
This command clears the terminal screen.
Example:
clear

14.man (Manual)
This command shows the manual or help for a command.
Example:
man ls

15.history
This command shows previously used commands.
Example:
history

16.whoami
This command shows the current user name.
Example:
whoami

17.date
This command shows the current date and time.
Example:
date

18.chmod (Change Mode)
This command changes file permissions.
Example:
chmod 755 file1.txt

19.wc (Word Count)
This command counts lines, words, and characters in a file.
Example:
wc file1.txt

20.head and tail
head shows first lines of a file.
tail shows last lines of a file.
Example:
head file1.txt
tail file1.txt

21.grep
This command searches text inside a file.
Example:
grep hello file1.txt